68, -0.0162893645465374, -0.02661234140396118, 0.016491996124386787, -0.04021120071411133, 0.0039175525307655334, 0.00926478672772646, 0.016593312844634056, 0.024068182334303856, 0.00883700791746378, 0.016007930040359497, 0.029291586950421333, 0.016356907784938812, 0.014848425053060055, -0.013396228663623333, 0.0039175525307655334, 0.0341997854411602, -0.0037092920392751694, -0.026139533147215843, -0.027715560048818588, -0.0347176231443882, 0.008375457488000393, 0.014420646242797375, 0.017212465405464172, 0.018889809027314186, -0.022424612194299698, 0.017865391448140144, -0.03985096514225006, -0.00645045330747962, 0.00990645494312048, -0.0015450692735612392, -0.020600924268364906, 0.005361306015402079, -0.03289393335580826, -0.007328525185585022, 0.017381325364112854, -0.005910100881010294, 0.0336594320833683, -0.001379727153107524, -0.018439514562487602, 0.007210323121398687]], "input": ["\"INVENTORY VALUATION AT STANDARD COST\":\"For internal management control, inventory is usually valued at its standard cost to highlight variances and encourage remedial action.\"", "\"GENERAL CAUSES OF VARIANCES\":\"General causes of variances include planning errors, measurement errors, random factors, and operational factors.\"", "\"SPECIFIC CAUSES OF VARIANCES\":\"Specific causes of variances can be categorized as favourable or adverse, such as bulk discounts, market price increases, better quality materials, defective materials, lower skilled labour, wage rises, and strikes.\"", "\"QUIZ: RECONCILIATION\":\"This quiz involves preparing an operating statement for the period under marginal costing, including budgeted contribution, sales margin variances, standard profit on actual sales, cost variances, and actual profit.\"", "\"LABOUR RATE\":\"Labour rate refers to the cost of labor, which can be influenced by factors such as lower skilled labor, wage rises, overtime working, and bonus payments.\"", "\"IDLE TIME\":\"Idle time is the period when employees or machines are not productive due to factors like strikes, lack of material, breakdowns, injury/illness, or lack of orders.\"", "\"LABOUR EFFICIENCY\":\"Labour efficiency measures the productivity of labor, which can be positively influenced by motivation, higher pay, better equipment, learning effect, better material, and higher skill, or negatively influenced by lower pay, poor equipment, slow working, poor material, and lower skill.\"", "\"OVERHEAD EXPENDITURE\":\"Overhead expenditure refers to the costs associated with running a business that are not directly tied to production. These can include cost savings/cutbacks, cost increases, excessive service usage, and incorrect split of semi-variable and fixed costs.\"", "\"OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY\":\"Overhead efficiency measures how effectively overhead costs are managed, often related to labor efficiency.\"", "\"OVERHEAD CAPACITY\":\"Overhead capacity refers to the productive hours available for overheads, which can be affected by increases in productive hours, excessive idle time, and shortage of plant capacity.\"", "\"SALES PRICE\":The \"Sales Price\" is the amount at which a product or service is sold to customers, measured in dollars. It is a critical factor in determining the revenue and profitability of a business. The sales price can be influenced by various factors, including market shortages, the need to increase sales volume, changes in product quality, responses to competitors, and the necessity to pass on cost changes.", "\"INTERDEPENDENCE OF VARIANCES\":\"Interdependence of variances refers to the situation where two or more variances are caused by the same operational factor, necessitating consideration of the overall effect when taking action.\"", "\"VARIANCE ANALYSIS FORMULAE\":\"Formulae for variances include calculations for sales volume, sales price, materials price, materials usage, labor rate, idle time, labor efficiency, variable overhead rate, variable overhead efficiency, fixed overhead expenditure, fixed overhead volume, fixed overhead capacity, and fixed overhead efficiency.\"", "\"ADVANCED VARIANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Advanced variance analysis includes material mix and yield variances, sales mix and quantity variances, and performance analysis.\"", "\"MATERIAL MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES\":\"Material mix and yield variances involve calculating, identifying causes, and explaining variances related to the mix and yield of materials used in production.\"", "\"SALES MIX AND QUANTITY VARIANCES\":\"Sales mix and quantity variances involve calculating, identifying causes, and explaining variances related to the mix and quantity of sales.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}